We recommended that management:
require the Local Finance Committee to conduct a comprehensive analysis to determine and ensure that all liabilities are with available cash support to ensure unhampered implementation of PPAs;
ensure that trust funds are used exclusively to the purpose/s for which they were granted following the provisions of Section 4(3) of P.D. No. 1445 and Sections 305(e) and 309(b) of R.A. No. 7160;
require the settlement of long outstanding receivables to augment the deficient cash under trust fund; and
adopt cost-saving / economic measures.

The concerned personnel stated that they have started analyzing all liabilities, receivables, and cash equivalents as recommended. During this analysis, it was discovered that some liabilities and receivables have been outstanding for an extended period without supporting documents. As a result, further comprehensive analysis will continue to determine the necessary actions to ensure the smooth implementation of various projects, programs, and activities.

6.2.7	We recommended that management require the observance of the following procedures:
conduct a thorough physical inventory of all PPEs to identify unserviceable items that need to be disposed of in accordance with the relevant laws and regulations;
once unserviceable items are identified, management should initiate the appropriate disposal procedures as prescribed by regulations. This may include destruction/condemnation, public auction, private/negotiated sale, or transfer to other government agencies;
after disposal, management should update the RPCPPE to reflect the removal of unserviceable items from the books; and
establish monitoring and review procedures to ensure that unserviceable items are promptly identified and disposed of in accordance with applicable laws and regulations.

6.2.12	We recommended that management require the observance of the following procedures:
the concerned personnel should immediately report missing PPE items to the Office of the Auditor by filing a notice of loss and applying for relief from property accountability and submitting available supporting evidence as required in Commission on Audit Memorandum No. 92-751. This should be done within the reglementary period of 30 days from the occurrence of the loss, as required by COA guidelines;
the GSO-designate should determine the employees responsible for the lost/missing items by examining its copies of Property Acknowledgement Receipts (PARs); and
there should be training and awareness programs to accountable officers and personnel involved in asset management to ensure understanding and compliance with reporting requirements for missing government property.

We recommended that the management:
conduct a review of the purposes for which funds were transferred to ensure compliance with memorandum of agreement or other documents prescribing their proper and timely utilization;
identify and analyze the root causes of delays in project implementation through a comprehensive review of plans and applicable processes;
establish monitoring mechanisms to track the utilization of transferred funds and ensure compliance with intended purposes; and
if warranted, request from the source agency the authority for the utilization of funds for other purposes by providing proper justifications to support its necessity, otherwise, the unutilized amounts should be returned to fully liquidate the transferred funds.

Management has committed to review the purposes for the funds transferred to comply with the memorandum of agreement, identifying causes of delay in the project implementation, and establishing mechanisms to track fund utilization. As to the funds still needing to be fully utilized (Financial Assistance for Cultural Mapping and the OPV-SIA Immunazion), the municipality is already processing its return as the cultural mapping project was already finished, while the latter program was implemented using LGU funds.

We recommended that the LGU should implement enhanced monitoring mechanisms to track the utilization of the 20% Development Fund, including any savings from completed or abandoned projects. This will help ensure that available funds are properly managed and allocated to priority development initiatives in the community. Specifically,
the MPDO should monitor and evaluate the implementation of the different development programs, projects, and activities in the local government unit concerned in accordance with the approved development plan and prepare recommendations for consideration of the Municipal Development Council;
the Municipal Development Council should coordinate, monitor, and evaluate the implementation of development programs and projects and prepare resolutions for consideration of the Sangguniang Bayan Office;
the Municipal Budget Officer to assist the MPDO and MDC in determining unexpended balances of completed/abandoned projects for subsequent reappropriation; and
the Sangguniang Bayan Office should enact an ordinance for the reappropriation of reverted unexpended balances of the 20% Development Fund to other development programs, projects, or activities, ensuring efficient utilization of funds.

We recommended that management:
revert the unliquidated balances of liability accounts that have been outstanding for two years or more and lack valid claims or supporting documents to the unappropriated surplus;
Conduct a thorough review of all liability accounts to ensure they meet the criteria for recognition as per the provisions of IPSAS No. 1, namely: a) existence of a present obligation from past events, b) probability of outflow of resources embodying economic benefits, and c) reliable measurement of the obligation's cost/value;
ensure that all obligations are supported by valid claims, bills, relevant records, and valid proofs to warrant payment. This includes maintaining subsidiary ledgers for each creditor with adequate information to justify the existence of such obligations;
establish a system to monitor the age and validity of liability accounts regularly. This system should flag accounts that are nearing the two-year mark for review and potential reversion; and
communicate with potential creditors, especially for accounts that have been outstanding for an extended period. This will help in validating the existence of claims and facilitating their settlement or reversion as appropriate.

Management committed to address the recommendation by reverting unliquidated balances of liability accounts outstanding for two years or more, lacking valid claims and supporting documents, to the unappropriated surplus. Communication with potential creditors will be undertaken to validate claims and facilitate settlement or reversion. Additionally, a personnel was tasked to review all liability accounts to ensure compliance with recognition criteria provided by the International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS).

